 What is DOM Event Handling?

An event is something that happens in the browser: user clicks, types, moves the mouse, submits a form, etc.

Event handling means writing code that responds to these events.

Ways to Attach Event Handlers

Inline HTML Attribute

<button onclick="alert('Clicked!')">Click Me</button>


DOM Property

const btn = document.getElementById("myBtn");
btn.onclick = function() {
  alert("Clicked!");
};


addEventListener (Preferred)

const btn = document.getElementById("myBtn");
btn.addEventListener("click", function() {
  alert("Clicked!");
});


 Pros: Can attach multiple listeners, can remove later.

 Mouse Events

Mouse events happen when the user interacts with the mouse.

Event	Description
click	User clicks on an element
dblclick	Double click
mousedown	Mouse button pressed
mouseup	    Mouse button released
mouseover	Mouse enters element area
mouseout	Mouse leaves element area
mousemove	Mouse moves inside element

Example:

<div id="box" style="width:100px;height:100px;background:red;"></div>

<script>
const box = document.getElementById("box");

box.addEventListener("click", () => alert("Box clicked!"));
box.addEventListener("mouseover", () => box.style.background = "green");
box.addEventListener("mouseout", () => box.style.background = "red");
box.addEventListener("mousemove", (e) => {
    console.log(`Mouse at X:${e.clientX}, Y:${e.clientY}`);
});
</script>


e is the event object, contains info like mouse coordinates.

 Input Events

Input events happen when the user interacts with form elements.

Event	Description
input	Fires when the value of an input changes (typing)
change	Fires when input loses focus after value changed
focus	Input gains focus
blur	Input loses focus
keydown	Key is pressed down
keyup	Key is released
keypress	Key is pressed (deprecated in modern usage)

Example:

<input type="text" id="username" placeholder="Type here..." />

<script>
const input = document.getElementById("username");

// On every input change
input.addEventListener("input", (e) => {
  console.log("Typing:", e.target.value);
});

// When input loses focus
input.addEventListener("change", (e) => {
  console.log("Final value:", e.target.value);
});

// Focus and blur events
input.addEventListener("focus", () => console.log("Input focused"));
input.addEventListener("blur", () => console.log("Input blurred"));
</script>

 Tips:

Always prefer addEventListener over inline HTML.

Use event delegation for dynamic elements (attach event to parent).

The event object provides useful info:

e.target → the element where the event occurred

e.type → event type (click, input, etc.)

e.preventDefault() → prevent default behavior (e.g., form submission)

e.stopPropagation() → stop bubbling up